WEBVTT

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:07.360
All right. Hi, everyone. So I am JP Helveston. I am a systems engineering professor at George

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:12.640
Washington University. And yeah, I'm excited to share with you our platform that we've developed

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:22.719
called SurveyDown. In my research, I try to figure out what people want. I study people.

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:28.959
And I'm in the field of sustainable energy. So I try to understand things like under what

00:00:28.959 --> 00:00:34.720
conditions would you buy an electric car or solar panels, those kinds of cleaner technologies.

00:00:35.919 --> 00:00:40.959
Now, I don't have a crystal ball. And I am a professor. But I'm not this kind of professor.

00:00:41.599 --> 00:00:46.799
So I can't read your minds. And I have to rely on other tools to learn from you. So I rely on

00:00:46.799 --> 00:00:53.040
surveys to understand people and their preferences. I use web-based surveys. Most web surveys look

00:00:53.040 --> 00:01:01.520
something like this. You know, there's different types of questions. People can type through them.

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:07.199
The questions are all on different pages. This is near the end of a survey here. And chances are,

00:01:07.199 --> 00:01:10.879
if you've ever made a survey, it probably looks something like this as well, some sort of web

00:01:12.639 --> 00:01:17.839
survey with forms on different pages. And if you've ever made a web survey, you've probably

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:23.919
used a tool that looks something like this. This is, of course, Google Forms. But whether it's

00:01:23.919 --> 00:01:29.839
Google Forms or Qualtrics or any other kind of survey software, it's usually a what you see is

00:01:29.839 --> 00:01:36.320
what you get interface. And that interface is really nice for really basic surveys because

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:41.279
it's intuitive, easy to use. But it does have a lot of limitations, especially as a research tool.

00:01:42.239 --> 00:01:48.800
So first of all, they're fundamentally not reproducible. If I want to recreate someone else's

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:53.760
survey, I have to go hand make it and click and drag things and add content manually.

00:01:55.120 --> 00:02:00.320
They're also kind of difficult to version control. So if you've ever made versions of a survey,

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:05.279
your Google Drive starts to look a little bit... This clicker is not working, so I'm going to just

00:02:05.279 --> 00:02:10.160
do that. Look like this, right? Lots and lots of forms and versions of those forms, and it's just

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:15.839
not working great. They also have limited features. I can only ask questions that are

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:20.240
provided by the software. If there's other custom questions I want to ask, it might be hard to

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:26.399
implement. And it's not open source. Most of them are not open source. So I have limited ability to

00:02:26.399 --> 00:02:32.080
further customize the tool or understand what's going on under the hood. But this is a session

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:37.119
on Cordo, right? And Cordo, this is like the feature set, right? It's like all of those things

00:02:37.119 --> 00:02:41.919
are what you get with Cordo. I'm a huge fan of it. It is reproducible. You get version control

00:02:41.919 --> 00:02:46.000
with GitHub. All of that is for free because you're just editing a plain text document.

00:02:47.039 --> 00:02:51.360
It is very feature packed, right? You can run code. So anything that you can stick in code,

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:58.399
you can run inside those documents. And it's open source. So as a big fan of Cordo and a

00:02:58.399 --> 00:03:03.279
survey researcher, I couldn't help but think this question, wouldn't it be nice if there was a Cordo

00:03:03.279 --> 00:03:08.399
for surveys, right? You just edit a Cordo doc, render, and get survey. And I asked a lot of

00:03:08.399 --> 00:03:13.759
people, could you make this for me? And nobody was willing to do it. So we decided, fine, we'll

00:03:13.759 --> 00:03:18.559
just make it ourselves. And we made a package called SurveyDown. So it's obviously a pun on

00:03:18.559 --> 00:03:22.800
Markdown here. But the idea is Markdown-based surveys. That was the sort of vision.

00:03:23.679 --> 00:03:29.679
So in my talk today, I'm going to try and walk you through what it is, how does this package work,

00:03:30.479 --> 00:03:34.240
what are some of the cool things you can do with it, and then where we're going next. We

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:38.080
have some further developments this past summer even that we've been working on.

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:44.720
So what is it? It is an R package. And in a nutshell, it tries to take Cordo files and

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:50.399
render them into surveys. So that's the gist of what SurveyDown is all about. So I think the

00:03:50.399 --> 00:03:55.440
easiest way to explain that is to just show you a really basic example. So this little survey you

00:03:55.440 --> 00:04:00.160
see on the screen here that just has a header, one question, and an X button. If you wanted to

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:06.479
make that, this is the file you would need. All right? So this is just a normal Cordo document.

00:04:06.479 --> 00:04:12.000
There's nothing really special about it. It has a YAML at the top. We're rendering to HTML. We

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.440
have some settings so that you don't see messages and things like that. You have the SurveyDown R

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:21.760
package that you need to load. And then the rest of this is the content that you're going to see

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:28.559
on that survey. All right? So pages are defined using the Cordo fence thing, right? Those little

00:04:28.559 --> 00:04:33.440
three colons. If you've ever used those to control where things are displayed in a Cordo doc,

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:39.760
we kind of took advantage of that. And each Cordo fence has this SD page class, SD there being for

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:44.559
SurveyDown, with a unique ID. All right? So everything inside those fences, that's what's

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:48.559
going to be on that page. And of course, you can have multiple pages on your survey.

00:04:48.559 --> 00:04:53.279
So for this little survey, we're going to put that welcome message with a header level one,

00:04:53.279 --> 00:04:57.600
that's the little hashtag, and then we have a code chunk where we're defining survey questions

00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:02.880
and a next button. All right? So that stuff that's highlighted right there, that's what you're seeing

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:09.440
in this rendered page on the right. So that is the gist of how we define surveys using

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:14.640
SurveyDown. I want to highlight one more little small thing here, which is that every call to

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:19.519
SD question, that's our main survey question function, has an ID and an option list. And so

00:05:19.519 --> 00:05:24.320
that ID that says has fave hero, that's going to be the unique ID for this question. It's also going

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:28.399
to be the name of the variable that you get in the resulting data. All right? So it's going to say

00:05:28.399 --> 00:05:34.160
has fave hero. And then the option list, you'll see that there's a name and a value. And so the

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:39.600
name, the capital Y for yes, that's going to be what's shown in the survey. The lowercase y for

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:43.119
yes is what you get in your data. So I'm just highlighting that because you get to control

00:05:43.119 --> 00:05:47.519
everything about your survey, including what you see on the survey as well as what the data looks

00:05:47.519 --> 00:05:50.959
like that you get back, which is something that we were very intentional about. If you've ever

00:05:50.959 --> 00:05:57.519
worked with survey data, you know how much of a pain that can be. Okay. So if you've used Cordo,

00:05:57.519 --> 00:06:01.440
you know that it renders to static pages. So you might be wondering how in the world do we go from

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:08.480
static page to web survey? Well, we just needed some sort of web framework in R. It turns out

00:06:08.480 --> 00:06:13.040
there's been one that we've had for a very, very long time called Shiny. And so we thought,

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:19.200
why not just use that? And that's what we did. So this picture I showed you earlier saying that,

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:22.720
you know, we're just taking Cordo docs and turning them into surveys, that's not really

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:28.000
the complete picture. The more correct picture is this. We're actually building Shiny apps. So

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.559
every survey down survey is just a Shiny app. It's a standalone Shiny app. And we're just using

00:06:32.559 --> 00:06:37.839
Cordo to control the UI, which is what you see in the survey. And of course, with every Shiny app,

00:06:37.839 --> 00:06:43.679
there's also a server in the background that's running all the logic. So this is the correct

00:06:43.679 --> 00:06:49.040
picture to think about how survey down really works. So a complete survey is actually two files.

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:52.720
You need your Cordo file. That's where you're going to define all the contents that's inside

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:57.440
your survey, like the one I just showed you. And you need some sort of small app.r script that's

00:06:57.440 --> 00:07:03.279
defining a Shiny app. Now, if you've never used Shiny, don't panic. We've tried to make it as

00:07:03.279 --> 00:07:07.760
easy as possible for you. Really the main thing you need to know about Shiny is that it needs two

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:14.799
pieces, a UI and a server. So we wrote two functions, stui and stserver. And that's it. It's

00:07:14.799 --> 00:07:20.320
pretty much a boilerplate file. You don't really have to worry about this file very much. The stui

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:24.720
function is going to render that Cordo file for you. You don't even have to render it yourself.

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:28.959
And stserver is going to handle all the logic about page turning and data management and stuff

00:07:28.959 --> 00:07:35.760
like that. Okay. So now we have a web survey. But you might be thinking, where does the data

00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:40.320
go? People are filling out our web form, so it has to go somewhere. And we thought about this,

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:45.519
too. We needed some sort of data back end that's going to store your responses. But we wanted to

00:07:45.519 --> 00:07:51.839
use, again, exclusively open source technologies. So we landed on Postgres as our main decision

00:07:51.839 --> 00:07:57.040
here to just go with that for now. And it's working really well. Now, just like Shiny,

00:07:57.040 --> 00:08:00.880
don't panic. If you've never used Postgres or you've never set up your own database, we've

00:08:00.959 --> 00:08:05.839
tried to make this as easy as possible as well. For one, a great starting point is to use

00:08:05.839 --> 00:08:12.320
Superbase. So Superbase.com is a wonderful website that gives you free access to a database.

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:17.440
And you can set it up when you log in and make a table. It looks like this. It looks just like

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:21.359
something like a Google sheet or anything like that. You'll see your responses coming in,

00:08:21.359 --> 00:08:26.880
one row per respondent. So all you really need to do is get a Postgres database somewhere,

00:08:26.880 --> 00:08:31.920
whether it's Superbase or some other server that you set up. That's fine. Get your credentials.

00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:35.919
And that's really all you need is you need to hand your credentials to SurveyDown,

00:08:35.919 --> 00:08:40.640
and you're good to go. So this is the last little step to make that little handshake work.

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:45.359
You have to make a connection to that database. So we have a little function here called sddb

00:08:45.359 --> 00:08:50.239
connect. Once you have that connection, you pass it to the server, and the server will take care

00:08:50.239 --> 00:08:54.479
of all the data management for you. You'll see there's one more little function at the top called

00:08:54.559 --> 00:08:59.599
sddb config. That's commented out because you just need to run that one time. That's just to set up

00:08:59.599 --> 00:09:03.520
your configuration. So you get your credentials like your host and your password, stuff like that,

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:07.599
store it as a little environment variable, and then basically forget about it.

00:09:08.479 --> 00:09:15.119
Okay, so that is one of the nice things about using this sort of separate database to store

00:09:15.119 --> 00:09:19.919
your data is now you can have a workflow where you have one project where you have everything

00:09:19.919 --> 00:09:23.440
about your survey in one place, right? So you can see in my tabs here, I have the survey

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:28.640
cordo file, I have the app.r file, and I also have this analysis file where I'm, again, connecting

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:32.880
to that database and pulling the data in right away. So in one place, I can design my survey

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:39.599
and also analyze the data as it's coming in. So what is SurveyDown? Well, it is our package,

00:09:39.599 --> 00:09:44.239
but it's a little bit more than that. It's really like an ecosystem. We've actually are pulling on

00:09:44.239 --> 00:09:48.559
a lot of other open source technologies to make this all work. We're using Cordo for designing

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:54.719
the survey, Shiny as our web framework, and Postgres to store the survey data, and the R package

00:09:54.719 --> 00:09:58.479
is really just making all of that work together and providing the control logic.

